rley, Buckinghamshire, England":"Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England","Tarvin, Cheshire, England":"Tarvin, Cheshire, England","Bray Hundred, Berkshire, England":"Bray Hundred, Berkshire, England","England":"England","London, England":"London, England","Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England":"Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Norreys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Norris  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Norris","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Middle English <i>norreis</i>, <i>noreis</i>, <i>norais</i> ‘northerner’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>noreis</i>), used both of Norwegians and of inhabitants of northern England and Scotland.","from the Middle English personal name <i>Norreis</i>, derived from <i>norreis</i> ‘northerner’."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":53,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Norreys was born in 1402, in Tarvin, Cheshire, England, her father, Sir William Norreys Esq of  Ockwells, was 27 and her mother, Lady Christina Strech, was 20. She married Thomas William Bulstrode about 1430, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1462, in England, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1402–1462":"1402–1462","1400–1466":"1400–1466","1405–1478":"1405–1478","1420–1478":"1420–1478","1420–1502":"1420–1502","1446–1517":"1446–1517","1375–1466":"1375–1466","1382–1425":"1382–1425","1462":"1462","1382":"1382","1425":"1425","1502":"1502","1402":"1402","1446":"1446","1478":"1478","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","about 1420":"umbes 1420","about 1430":"umbes 1430","1517":"1517","1405":"1405","Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England":"Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England","Tarvin, Cheshire, England":"Tarvin, Cheshire, England","Bray Hundred, Berkshire, England":"Bray Hundred, Berkshire, England","England":"England","London, England":"London, England","Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England":"Heytesbury, Wiltshire, England"},"fi":{"1402–1462":"1402–1462","1400–1466":"1400–1466","1405–1478":"1405–1478","1420–1478":"1420–1478","1420–1502":"1420–1502","1446–1517":"1446–1517","1375–1466":"1375–1466","1382–1425":"1382–1425","1462":"1462","1382":"1382","1425":"1425","1502":"1502","1402":"1402","1446":"1446","1478":"1478","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","about 1420":"noin 1420","about 1430":"noin 1430","1517":"1517","1405":"1405","Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England":"Hedgerley, Buckinghamshire, England","Tarvin, Cheshire, England":"Tarvin, Cheshire, England","Bray